segments.text: So he said, okay, you run over there and drive over there as fast as you can and get back here and we will hold up and watch you do that.

So that boy held up the processional until I could get back and we walked up on stage and I had just a notebook and I had an old speech and I took my pen out and I wrote down on one single piece of paper some points out of that
and just kind of reviewed the old speech while all the welcomes and everything had been going on.
Because I only had about 10 minutes until I had to be up there.
And then I got up and
gave the commencement, and I don't think that most of them ever knew that I wasn't supposed to have been the one to give it.
It was a wonderful time.
Did your colleagues give you any credit later?
Oh, yeah.
In fact, when I left the president's office, the president's staff gave me
a big drawing that was made by a man here on campus that had the major things that happened during my career at those levels.
And one of them was, here's a picture of Bill Mobley saying, you're the commencement speaker this morning.
And it had a lot of things in it.
It had like move into the Big 12.
I helped get the new Texas Clipper for the campus at Galveston.
They had that on it.
It had the Sweet Sixteen basketball, which was the only time our girls basketball team had ever gone that far, and a lot of things like that.
And it had gauges, rules for administration.
They had all ten of them on there.
And I was so proud that they put number one of integrity, because that was what I tried to instill through every component that answered to me.
What else have we not?
I don't know.
Right.
As you walked away from those years of leadership, for what were you most proud?
And then were there any things that you wish you could have done, but you weren't able to?
I would have to tell you that I was most proud for two things.
One is that when I have gone back to be introduced, the introduction has been, here was a leader of character and integrity.
The second was the advancements that we made in every academic program at the university and the leadership that we recruited
to lead those programs.
What would I like to have seen happen that I didn't get done?
That's a tough question.
Probably the final resolution to some of the difficult issues that I was bringing to closure at the time.
That it would have been best had there been a longer period passed from the time I brought it to closure to the time a new person had taken it.
Because they still had to live with a little of that around
That really would have been it.
And somebody sitting here might not tell you that, but in all honesty, I would want people to know that.
I really would.
In the search processes, as we now do it, with comparatively long and involved, lots of committees,
In fact, are those searches as successful as they used to be when they were done more direct?

I personally do not think so because I think too many times in search processes that in the academic area that too much is placed on what the resume, the curriculum VT, the academic credential might be with a real
vacuum of looking, can that person lead people?
And I tell you, I didn't use that philosophy when I would go talk to people about recruiting a dean or department head.
I would tell them, I want to see written into this that this person is also a leader and can lead and has administrative abilities.
Because I said, we could bring a National Academy of Science person in here
that couldn't administrate their way out of a paper bag.
I said, we want to do a background to know that they can lead.
And I said, I want you to ask questions.
I'm going to ask questions.
I'm going to look at that.
So don't bring me somebody only on paper.
And I think that it gets so wound up today in just the academic credential side, the curriculum VT side, rather than what are their people skills, because leadership
could be summed up in one word.
Leadership is people.
Period.
The people skills.
Earl Rudder wasn't much of a scholar, and Jack Williams wasn't a native Texan that hadn't been to A&M, but they both did a good job because they had some, and they both had integrity.
That's right.
Now, throughout all this, what role did your faith, your personal faith play?
My personal faith played an enormous part in it.
mainly because it kept me on the straight and narrow track that I would never do anything that would be questionable.
I would never compromise the truth or integrity in any way.
And I was very committed to the fact that my character
would outlast and my name would outlast any other thing.
You know, I'll be honest with you, every morning I would have a prayer.
And my prayer was that I would have the sound wisdom that day to make the right judgment decision on the many decisions that I had to make.
And secondly,
that my own personal character and integrity would never be compromised or questioned by anyone around me.
And you were a member of what congregation?
I was a member of Central Baptist Church here at Bryan College Station.
All those years?
All those years.
And still?
That's right.
And it was a growing congregation, but comparatively small in the 70s and 80s, wasn't it?
Oh, yeah, compared to where it is now.
It's 5,000 members now.
It just bought 65 acres to look to relocate and expand again.
Let's make believe that you are now hired to be a consultant to Texas A&M.
What advice would you give Texas A&M and its leadership today?
I would give them the advice to never compromise the traditions and value systems of the past and to recruit leadership that would be committed to what this university stands for.
and to put in place a strategic plan that this leadership could buy into to move this university to top 10 status.
I think a lot of that's already in place, but I would not want to see anyone come in and deviate away from those.
We see so many other
institutions, both academic, higher education, and other, that have begun to cave in to political correctness over what is right.
And it takes a lot of courage today for administrators to stand up and to make the decisions that are based on what's right and what's wrong, what's honest, what's integrity.
and not cave in to the political correctness crowd that's out there.
To stay the course.
I think they'll gain greater respect and achieve a whole lot more if they will do that.
What did you learn here as an A&M student?

that proved to be important to you later what did you learn about as an Aggie well I learned so much as an Aggie about I really believe the values and things in life that are important as well as a work ethic and I

a respect for that which had been given to me in the way of a trust of my being a graduate of this institution to the point that I would never want to do anything that would reflect negatively on this university.
To me, it was similar to growing up as a young man.
I didn't want to do anything that my mom and dad would be ashamed of me doing.
Well, I never wanted to do anything that my university would be ashamed of me doing.
That was so reinforced through just the trust, I think, that had been put in us to be a student and the privilege of being a student here.
Maybe it was because I had to work so hard
to be able to work my way through this university.
It was not something given to me.
It was only given to me through great sacrifice of my parents and myself.
So I learned a lot of that as a student here that carried on through really the rest of my life.
I also learned what it meant to care for other people.
You hear this, it's the Aggie family, it's the Aggie spirit.
That's still true.
And you learn to care for what happens to those around you.
And when they have a need, you go to them.
When you have a need, they come to you.
Those are the main ones.
All right.
Typist, take this question and the response and put it back two or three questions.
I should have asked this just before ask about the consultant.

as you look back on all your A&M years, to whom, and if all the people involved in those years could be called together, to which ones would you express the greatest appreciation for what they've meant to you?
To whom are you most grateful?
I would be most grateful to Al Price, who was the dean of veterinary college early.

and when I was a faculty member at A&M the first time as a student, and then later after I'd been to Auburn as a faculty member, to George Shelton for bringing me back here in 1982, and clearly to Bill Mobley when he was president of the university.
All of those had an influence and an impact in my own personal career, and I would give them a lot of gratitude, no question.
And then,
I would say the associate provost who served with me in the provost office.
Who?
Jeanette Ferris, Jerry Gaston, Bill Perry, Danny Parker, Sally Shepard.
I won't leave anybody out because of all the teams of people that I had the privilege of working with,
we probably had as effective and efficient team that got things done as any team of people I ever worked with in my life.
And I told the deans when I took that position, I said, when you send something up there, you're gonna get an answer.
I said, you're gonna get a yes, no, or I'm gonna tell you why I can't give you an answer right now, but it's not gonna get lost.
And you're gonna get a response, you're gonna get a turnaround, and I'm gonna be decisive.
And I'm going to make what I think is the best decision for the university.
And you know, I didn't always please them because I had turned some of them down.
So that would really be the team of people.
During those years with lots of pressure, what did you do to relax?
Well, early when I still had time, I jogged and got some exercise.
Later on, when I was, the last two or three years of being provost and the presidency, there were not many times too relaxed.
About the only thing I could do would be go home at night and just crash in the chair and maybe watch television or something.
But if I were to do it over again, I personally would try to allocate some time for particularly exercise.
I said, I don't have time to exercise.
Well, you don't.
You have to make time.
And you just have to do those things.

Let's make believe that someone walks up to you with a check for a million dollars and places only one restriction on that, and that restriction is you must pass it to Texas A&M, but you decide what use will be made of that money.
If you had the opportunity to make a big gift, A&M, what would you want it to be for?
If I had the opportunity to give a million dollar gift, designate where it went, it would go to student scholarships.
And the reason I say that is that I probably could not have got started in college had it not been for
some academic scholarships that were given to me the first year.
And secondly, A&M has protected still selecting a lot of students that are maybe not from the wealthy families and they're not in the highest rank of their class or something.
They're still taking just the students that have to work for a lot of what they get.
And over the years, I've watched those students
And I've had so many of them come back to me, students who I encouraged to get in.
And I've watched them over the years and their achievements.
And that's been such a great reward for me to see them.
Under your program, would they be restricted by major or geography?
No, absolutely not.
How do you identify which ones are most deserving?
I probably would just simply give it
to the university and ask that it be given to students based on financial need to help them to be able to go.
I tell you one other reason, too, in that I saw students, particularly in the College of Veterinary Medicine, graduate with such an overwhelming debt.
And my wife and I, right now through our church, adopt about six to ten students a year that we just kind of become second parents to while they're here.
And there's a little girl that's the sweetest little girl.
Her mother and dad probably could have never given her a penny.
She worked her way through A&M.
She's now got a terrific job, but she left here with probably about $30,000 or $40,000 in debt.
And if it could help a girl like that,
She's the first one from either side of her family.
In fact, I felt so sorry for her because her dad did not even come to her graduation.
That broke my heart.
In fact, I'd like to have kicked him.
How sad.
How sad.
Like one of the things that doesn't have anything to do with this interview except another good point.
Dr. Williams.
at the end of commencements would have the honor students stand, the 3-5, the 3-7-5, dah, dah, dah.
Then he would say, now I want those students to stand who are the first in their family to finish college.
Oh, I wish I'd have thought to have done that.
And there would be some mothers reaching.
Oh, man.
Then he'd say, but now I want
the most worthy people in this room to stand.
The parents of us.
I want the parents of these to stand.
I wish I had known that.
I would have done that.
Well, I stole that idea and used it over and over and over.
I would love to have done that.
Because most people don't think that there are still those situations as often as there are.
Oh, there still are.
That's right.
Yes.
Let's see.
Two other questions.
What does it mean to be an Aggie?
What does it mean to be an Aggie?
I bet that question's been asked and answered millions of times.
To me, it means to be a graduate and former student of Texas A&M University.
who has been given something in life that will last a lifetime.
And that something is in part the family, the value, the traditions that
yield a purpose in life.
I don't know, I could add a lot more.
Last question.
What are your feelings, what are the feelings that are in your heart today about A&M?
Well, I could never be more proud of A&M than I am of A&M today.
And, you know, where it stands
nationally, internationally as a university.
I travel the country a lot right now, all over the U.S. And when people find out that I was a former president of A&M, they have great respect.
And I could not be more proud of my university than I am of where it is today and where I think it's going in the future.
I must admit that there are a few things
probably that have been done in the past several years for political correctness that I would prefer to not see done.
I regret that the anti-discrimination policy was changed.
I regret that I have heard that they have cut out prayer at football games.
I do not know that, but I heard that recently.
I hope that hasn't happened, and I hope it never happens.
I would never want to see the basic foundations changed.
I think Dr. Bowen has done a superb job.
I stand fully with him in Bonfire, and I honestly believe I would have taken the exact same actions, and I just hope and pray that no renegade
Bonfire takes place because that is not action that is consistent with the Aggie spirit and honor code or code of honor.
That's a great thing.
